[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 8.4: Medication Extraction and Normalization
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Medium · **Phase:** Integration · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.002-0.01 per note
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A hospitalist is admitting a patient at 2 AM. The patient's medication list in the EHR says "lisinopril 10mg daily." The patient says they take "that blood pressure pill, the small white one, and also something for my cholesterol." The nursing home transfer summary mentions "Zestril 20mg PO QD" and "atorvastatin calcium 40mg QHS." The discharge summary from three months ago at a different facility lists "HCTZ/lisinopril 12.5/20" and "Lipitor 40."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Same patient. Same medications. Five different representations. And right now, at 2 AM, the hospitalist needs an accurate, reconciled medication list to avoid prescribing something that interacts with what the patient is already taking.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This isn't a rare scenario. It's the default state of medication documentation in healthcare. Clinicians write medications in every possible format: brand names, generic names, abbreviations, shorthand sig codes, partial descriptions, and sometimes just the drug class ("on a statin"). The same medication appears differently in progress notes versus discharge summaries versus nursing assessments versus pharmacy records. A single clinical note might mention "metformin 500 BID," "glucophage," and "her diabetes medication" all referring to the same drug.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The consequences of getting this wrong are not abstract. Adverse drug events from medication errors injure over a million people annually in the US alone. A significant portion of those stem from incomplete or inaccurate medication lists during transitions of care: admission, discharge, transfer, handoff. The Joint Commission has identified medication reconciliation as a National Patient Safety Goal for over a decade, and yet the problem persists because the underlying data problem (medications documented in unstructured text with infinite variation) hasn't been solved at the extraction layer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The information is there, buried in clinical notes. Extracting it reliably, normalizing it to a standard terminology so that "Zestril 20mg PO QD" and "lisinopril 20mg by mouth daily" are understood as the same thing, and structuring the dose, route, and frequency into machine-readable fields: that's the problem we're solving here.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Named Entity Recognition for Medications
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What Is Medical NER?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Named Entity Recognition (NER) is the NLP task of identifying specific types of entities in unstructured text and classifying them into predefined categories. In general NLP, those categories might be "person," "organization," "location." In clinical NLP, the categories that matter are "medication," "dosage," "route," "frequency," "duration," "condition," and "reason."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Medical NER is a specialized variant trained on clinical text rather than news articles or web pages. This distinction matters enormously because clinical language is nothing like general English. Physicians write in a compressed, abbreviated style full of domain jargon: "ASA 325 PO QD for afib" is a perfectly normal sentence in a clinical note. A general-purpose NER system would struggle with every token in that phrase.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The core approach to NER has evolved through several generations:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Rule-based systems** (1990s-2000s): Dictionary lookups and pattern matching. You build a list of known drug names and scan for them. Works decently for exact matches. Falls apart on abbreviations, misspellings, and novel formulations. Still useful as a preprocessing step.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Statistical models** (2000s-2010s): Conditional Random Fields (CRFs) and similar sequence labeling models trained on annotated clinical text. These learn patterns from context (what words typically surround a dosage? what follows a drug name?). The i2b2 shared tasks from 2009-2010 established benchmarks here.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Deep learning models** (2015-present): BiLSTM-CRF architectures and then transformer-based models (BioBERT, ClinicalBERT, PubMedBERT) fine-tuned on clinical NER datasets. These represent the current state of the art. They handle context, abbreviations, and novel formulations much better than earlier approaches because they learn distributed representations of clinical language.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Pre-trained medical NLP services** (2018-present): Cloud-managed services that package trained clinical NER models behind an API. You send text, you get back structured entities. No model training, no GPU infrastructure, no annotation pipeline. The accuracy is competitive with custom-trained models for common entity types (medications, conditions, anatomy) and dramatically easier to deploy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Normalization Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Extracting "lisinopril 20mg PO QD" from a note is only half the battle. The harder half is normalization: mapping that extraction to a standard code in a recognized terminology so that different systems can agree on what medication is being referenced.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The standard terminology for medications in the US is **RxNorm**, maintained by the National Library of Medicine. RxNorm assigns unique concept identifiers (RxCUIs) to clinical drugs at various levels of specificity:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Ingredient**: lisinopril (RxCUI: 29046)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Semantic Clinical Drug**: lisinopril 20 MG Oral Tablet (RxCUI: 314077)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Semantic Branded Drug**: Zestril 20 MG Oral Tablet (RxCUI: 104377)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Normalization means taking the raw extracted text and resolving it to the appropriate RxCUI. This is what enables a system to understand that "Zestril 20mg," "lisinopril 20 mg tab," and "Prinivil 20" all refer to the same clinical drug concept.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The challenges are substantial:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Brand vs. generic**: There are often dozens of brand names for a single generic ingredient. Atorvastatin alone has brand names including Lipitor, Sortis, Tulip, and Torvast (varying by country).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Combination drugs**: "HCTZ/lisinopril" or "Zestoretic" refers to a fixed-dose combination. The extraction system needs to identify both ingredients and their respective doses.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Abbreviations and shorthand**: "ASA" (aspirin), "MOM" (milk of magnesia), "APAP" (acetaminophen), "MTX" (methotrexate). These aren't in consumer dictionaries. Some are ambiguous: "MS" could be morphine sulfate or magnesium sulfate, and confusing them is a known cause of medication errors.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Dose form variations**: "lisinopril 20" might mean 20mg tablet or 20mg/5mL solution. Context (patient population, route) disambiguates, but it's not always explicit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sig parsing**: "1 tab PO BID PRN" needs to be decomposed into quantity (1), form (tablet), route (oral), frequency (twice daily), and condition (as needed). Sig codes follow loose conventions but aren't formally standardized across all documentation contexts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What Makes This Specifically Hard in Clinical Text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Clinical notes have properties that make NER harder than you'd expect from looking at clean pharmacy records:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Negation and context**: "Patient denies taking metformin" and "patient takes metformin" both contain the entity "metformin" but have opposite meanings. The extraction system must understand assertion context to build an accurate medication list.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Historical vs. current**: "Was on lisinopril, switched to losartan last month." Both are medications. Only one is current. The temporal context changes which belongs on the active list.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Allergies vs. medications**: "Allergic to penicillin. Currently taking amoxicillin." Wait. Both are mentioned. One is an allergy, one is a current medication. (And yes, this contradiction is clinically concerning, but that's a different problem.) The point is: not every medication mention belongs on the medication list.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Section-dependent meaning**: A medication mentioned in "Past Medical History" has different significance than one in "Medications on Admission." Section headers provide context that affects how extractions should be interpreted.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Dosage ambiguity**: "Increase metformin to 1000" could mean 1000mg or 1000mcg. Clinical context and the drug's typical dosing range disambiguate, but an NER system needs that knowledge or a validation layer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m At a conceptual level, the pipeline for medication extraction and normalization looks like this:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Clinical Note] → [Section Detection] → [NER Extraction] → [Attribute Linking] → [RxNorm Normalization] → [Context Classification] → [Structured Output]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Section Detection**: Identify which part of the note you're processing. Medications mentioned in "Assessment/Plan" are handled differently than those in "Allergies" or "Family History." This can be rule-based (look for common section headers) or model-based.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **NER Extraction**: Identify medication entities and their associated attributes (dose, route, frequency, duration, reason). The model labels each token with its entity type using BIO tagging (Beginning, Inside, Outside) or similar schemes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Attribute Linking**: Connect extracted attributes to their parent medication. "Lisinopril 20mg PO QD and metformin 500mg BID" has two medications, each with their own dose and frequency. The system needs to correctly associate 20mg/PO/QD with lisinopril, not metformin.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **RxNorm Normalization**: Map the extracted medication text (with dose and form if available) to a standard RxCUI. This typically involves fuzzy matching against the RxNorm database, with disambiguation logic for brand/generic equivalents and combination drugs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Context Classification**: Determine the assertion status of each extraction: is this medication currently active, historical, denied, or an allergy? This prevents building a medication list that includes discontinued drugs or allergies.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Structured Output**: Produce a machine-readable representation with the medication name, RxCUI, dose, route, frequency, status (active/discontinued/allergy), and confidence scores for each field.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Comprehend Medical for NER extraction.** Comprehend Medical is AWS's managed clinical NLP service. Its `DetectEntities` API performs medical NER across multiple entity categories, and it excels at medication extraction specifically. It returns medications with linked attributes (dosage, frequency, route, form, duration, condition/reason) already associated, which means you don't have to build the attribute-linking logic yourself. It also returns traits like "NEGATION" and "PAST_HISTORY" on extracted entities, giving you the context classification for free. The RxNorm normalization step is handled by a separate API (`InferRxNorm`) that takes medication text and returns ranked RxCUI candidates with confidence scores. Two API calls handle what would otherwise be three or four pipeline stages.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for note storage.** Clinical notes arrive from various sources (HL7 feeds, EHR exports, ADT messages). S3 provides encrypted staging for incoming notes and archival for processed results. Event-driven triggers (S3 notifications to Lambda) enable automatic processing as notes arrive.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for orchestration.** The extraction pipeline is stateless and short-lived: receive text, call Comprehend Medical, normalize results, store output. Lambda handles this naturally with automatic scaling. For batch processing (historical note backfill), Step Functions can orchestrate Lambda invocations with retry logic and progress tracking.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for medication list storage.** The normalized medication extractions need fast point-lookups by patient ID (for reconciliation workflows) and time-range queries (for medication history). DynamoDB's key-value model with sort keys supports both access patterns efficiently.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Step Functions for batch orchestration.** When processing thousands of historical notes, Step Functions provides workflow coordination, retry handling, and progress visibility that raw Lambda invocations lack.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart LR
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A[Clinical Note Source\nHL7/EHR/ADT] -->|Store| B[S3 Bucket\nnotes-inbox/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|S3 Event| C[Lambda\nmed-extractor]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|DetectEntities V2| D[Comprehend Medical]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D -->|Entities + Traits| C
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|InferRxNorm| E[Comprehend Medical\nRxNorm]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E -->|RxCUI Candidates| C
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Structured Meds| F[DynamoDB\npatient-medications]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Full Extraction| G[S3\nresults/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style B fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style D fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style E fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style F fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Comprehend Medical, Amazon S3, AWS Lambda, Amazon DynamoDB, AWS Step Functions (for batch) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `comprehend medical:DetectEntitiesV2`, `comprehendmedical:InferRxNorm`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:Query` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (required: clinical notes contain PHI) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default); Lambda CloudWatch log groups: KMS encryption (logs may contain extracted medication data); all API calls over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Lambda in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, Comprehend Medical, DynamoDB, and CloudWatch Logs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all Comprehend Medical and S3 API calls for HIPAA audit trail |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic clinical notes with medication mentions. MIMIC-III (with DUA) provides realistic note structures. Never use real patient notes in dev without proper IRB/DUA. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Comprehend Medical DetectEntities: ~$0.01 per 100 characters (minimum 3 units per request). InferRxNorm: ~$0.01 per 100 characters. A typical 2000-character note: ~$0.40 for detection + $0.02-0.10 for RxNorm inference per medication. Batch pricing available for high volume. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Comprehend Medical** | NER extraction (DetectEntitiesV2) and RxNorm normalization (InferRxNorm) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Stores incoming clinical notes and extraction results; encrypted with KMS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Orchestrates extraction: receives note, calls APIs, assembles structured output |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores normalized medication lists for patient-level queries |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Coordinates batch processing of historical notes |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Manages encryption keys for S3 and DynamoDB |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Logs, metrics, alarms for extraction failures and API throttling |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Preprocess and section-detect.** Clinical notes often arrive as a wall of text with section headers embedded ("MEDICATIONS:", "ASSESSMENT:", "ALLERGIES:"). Before sending text to the NER engine, we identify which sections contain medication-relevant content. This helps with downstream context classification: a medication found under "ALLERGIES" gets tagged differently than one under "CURRENT MEDICATIONS." Section detection can be rule-based for common note formats. Skip this step and you'll correctly extract medication entities but incorrectly classify allergies as active medications.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION detect_sections(note_text):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Common clinical note section headers that contain medication information.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // These patterns cover most structured clinical documentation formats.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     MEDICATION_SECTIONS = ["medications", "current medications", "home medications",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                           "medications on admission", "discharge medications",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                           "medication list", "meds"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ALLERGY_SECTIONS    = ["allergies", "drug allergies", "medication allergies"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     HISTORY_SECTIONS    = ["past medications", "prior medications", "medication history"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     sections = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Split note into sections by looking for header patterns.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Headers typically appear as "SECTION NAME:" or "**Section Name**" on their own line.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each line in note_text:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF line matches a section header pattern (ends with ":", is capitalized, etc.):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             current_section = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 header: normalized lowercase of header text,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 category: classify header into MEDICATION / ALLERGY / HISTORY / OTHER,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 start_position: character offset in original text,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 text: empty string
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append current_section to sections
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Append content to the current section being accumulated.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             current_section.text += line
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN sections
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Extract medication entities.** This is where the NER engine does its work. We send the clinical note text (or relevant sections) to Comprehend Medical's DetectEntitiesV2 API, which returns structured entities with their types, attributes, and traits. The key entity category we care about is MEDICATION, but we also need the associated attributes (DOSAGE, FREQUENCY, ROUTE_OR_MODE, FORM, DURATION, STRENGTH) and traits (NEGATION, PAST_HISTORY). The API handles the hard work of attribute linking: it knows that in "lisinopril 20mg PO QD," the 20mg belongs to lisinopril, not to whatever medication is mentioned next.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION extract_medications(note_text):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Call the managed NER service to extract medical entities from the note.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // DetectEntitiesV2 handles medications, conditions, anatomy, and more.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // We'll filter to medication-relevant entities afterward.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     response = call ComprehendMedical.DetectEntitiesV2 with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Text = note_text    // the raw clinical note text (max 20,000 characters per call)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     medications = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each entity in response.Entities:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Filter to medication entities only.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Comprehend Medical also returns MEDICAL_CONDITION, ANATOMY, etc.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF entity.Category == "MEDICATION":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             med = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 text:       entity.Text,           // the raw text span ("lisinopril 20mg")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 begin:      entity.BeginOffset,    // start character position in source text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 end:        entity.EndOffset,      // end character position
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 score:      entity.Score,          // confidence score 0.0-1.0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 attributes: empty map,             // will hold dose, route, freq, etc.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 traits:     empty list             // will hold NEGATION, PAST_HISTORY, etc.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Extract linked attributes (dose, route, frequency, etc.)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             FOR each attribute in entity.Attributes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 med.attributes[attribute.Type] = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     text:  attribute.Text,      // e.g., "20mg" or "twice daily"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     score: attribute.Score      // confidence for this specific attribute
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Extract traits that provide context about assertion status.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             FOR each trait in entity.Traits:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 append trait.Name to med.traits  // e.g., "NEGATION", "PAST_HISTORY"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append med to medications
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN medications
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Normalize to RxNorm.** Raw extraction gives us "lisinopril 20mg" as text. Normalization maps that to RxCUI 314077 (lisinopril 20 MG Oral Tablet), enabling interoperability with pharmacy systems, drug interaction databases, and formulary checks. The InferRxNorm API takes medication text and returns ranked candidate concepts with scores. We select the top candidate above a confidence threshold. For combination drugs and ambiguous abbreviations, the API returns multiple candidates that may need human adjudication.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m RXNORM_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD = 0.70  // below this, flag for pharmacist review
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION normalize_to_rxnorm(medication_text):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Send the extracted medication text to the RxNorm inference service.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // It returns ranked candidate RxNorm concepts with confidence scores.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     response = call ComprehendMedical.InferRxNorm with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Text = medication_text   // e.g., "lisinopril 20mg oral tablet"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     candidates = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each concept in response.Entities:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each rxnorm_concept in concept.RxNormConcepts:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append to candidates: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 rxcui:       rxnorm_concept.RxCUI,          // the RxNorm concept ID
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 description: rxnorm_concept.Description,    // standardized drug description
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 score:       rxnorm_concept.Score           // confidence 0.0-1.0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Sort by confidence and select the best match.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     sort candidates by score descending
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF candidates is not empty AND candidates[0].score >= RXNORM_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             rxcui:       candidates[0].rxcui,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             description: candidates[0].description,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             score:       candidates[0].score,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             status:      "MATCHED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF candidates is not empty:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Low confidence: return best guess but flag for review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             rxcui:       candidates[0].rxcui,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             description: candidates[0].description,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             score:       candidates[0].score,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             status:      "NEEDS_REVIEW"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // No candidates at all. Could be misspelling, abbreviation, or non-drug entity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             rxcui:       null,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             description: null,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             score:       0.0,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             status:      "UNMATCHED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Classify context and assertion status.** Not every medication mention belongs on the active medication list. This step uses the traits from Step 2 and the section information from Step 1 to determine what role each extracted medication plays. A medication with the NEGATION trait ("denies taking metformin") is classified differently from one in the ALLERGIES section ("allergic to penicillin"). Getting this wrong means populating a medication list with discontinued drugs, allergies, or medications the patient explicitly said they don't take.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION classify_medication_context(med, section_category):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Determine the assertion status of this medication mention.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Uses both NER traits (from the model) and section context (from preprocessing).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check for negation trait first: "not taking," "denies," "discontinued."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF "NEGATION" in med.traits:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN "NEGATED"      // patient is NOT taking this medication
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check for historical trait: "was on," "previously took," "prior to."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF "PAST_HISTORY" in med.traits:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN "HISTORICAL"   // medication was taken in the past, not currently active
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Use section context for classification.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF section_category == "ALLERGY":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN "ALLERGY"      // this is an allergy, not an active medication
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF section_category == "HISTORY":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN "HISTORICAL"   // found in a historical medications section
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF section_category == "MEDICATION":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN "ACTIVE"       // found in current medications section, no negation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Default for medications found in unstructured narrative (progress notes, etc.)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // without explicit negation or historical markers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN "ACTIVE"           // conservative default: treat as active unless proven otherwise
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Assemble and store structured medication records.** The final step combines all upstream outputs into a structured medication record for each extraction: the normalized drug identity (RxCUI), parsed attributes (dose, route, frequency), assertion status, confidence scores, and provenance (which note, which section, which character offsets). This record is what downstream systems consume for medication reconciliation, drug interaction checking, and clinical decision support.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION store_medication_extraction(patient_id, note_id, medications, sections):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     structured_meds = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each med in medications:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Determine which section this medication was found in.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         section = find section containing med.begin offset
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         context = classify_medication_context(med, section.category)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Normalize to RxNorm.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         rxnorm_result = normalize_to_rxnorm(med.text)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         structured_med = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient_id:      patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             note_id:         note_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             medication_text: med.text,                              // raw extracted text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             rxcui:           rxnorm_result.rxcui,                   // normalized drug identity
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             rxnorm_desc:     rxnorm_result.description,             // standardized description
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             rxnorm_score:    rxnorm_result.score,                   // normalization confidence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             rxnorm_status:   rxnorm_result.status,                  // MATCHED/NEEDS_REVIEW/UNMATCHED
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             dosage:          med.attributes.get("DOSAGE", null),    // e.g., "20mg"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             frequency:       med.attributes.get("FREQUENCY", null), // e.g., "twice daily"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             route:           med.attributes.get("ROUTE_OR_MODE", null),  // e.g., "oral"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             form:            med.attributes.get("FORM", null),      // e.g., "tablet"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             duration:        med.attributes.get("DURATION", null),  // e.g., "for 10 days"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             strength:        med.attributes.get("STRENGTH", null),  // e.g., "20 MG"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             assertion:       context,                               // ACTIVE/HISTORICAL/NEGATED/ALLERGY
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             confidence:      med.score,                             // overall extraction confidence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             source_section:  section.header,                        // which note section
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             extraction_ts:   current UTC timestamp (ISO 8601)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append structured_med to structured_meds
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write all extractions to the database.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Partition key: patient_id. Sort key: extraction_ts + note_id.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This enables queries like "all medications for patient X" and
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // "medications extracted from note Y."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     batch_write to DynamoDB table "patient-medications":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         items = structured_meds
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Also write full extraction details to S3 for audit and reprocessing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write JSON to S3: results/{patient_id}/{note_id}/medications.json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN structured_meds
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
